data.text:
Fates of a bunch of Famous People in a World with a stronger Latin America is a web series about an alternative world history with wacky versions of famous people throughout history. Some are based on real people. Others are fan made by internet users.

Antinous (110-130 AD), Roman statesman, stabbed in the back

Ptahhotep: Egyptian philosopher, nausea

Soichiro Honda: Japanese engineer, liver failure

Thomas Duquein: American short story writer, heart failure

Imhotep: Egyptian chancellor, fate unknown

Felicia Baak: female gang leader, lung cancer

Lidia Fetisova: model

The Buffalo Boys: a team of homeless boys who work as charity workers

Alvin Ailey, Jr.: dancer, natural causes

Dr. Linda James Myers: professor of Optimal Psychology

Hakim Orod Bozorg: Iranian philosopher and freedom fighter, founder of the Philosophy of Orodism

Dr. Philip Emeagwali: Nigerian entrepreneur

Ubuntu: Ngunti Bantu term meaning "humanity", often translated as "I am because we are" or "humanity towards others"

Christopher Emdin: professor in the Department of Mathematics, Science, and Technology at Teachers College in Columbia University

Taka: a wild African leopard, shot illegally by a poacher

Stafford Hood: professor at University of Illinois

素质 Suzhi: indigenous concept embedded in the centuries-long historical context of China

Angela Fitzgerald Ward: host of Wisconsin Life on PBS Wisconsin

Millard: albino moose discovered in Alaska, found dead with gunshot wounds in leg

Shivananda Khan: human rights activist

Dumpster: wild moose found at the bottom of a deep well, died from thirst due to the disgusting water

Molefi Kete Asante: American professor

Lee Yuk-wing: professor of Electrical Engineering at Massachusetts Institute of Technology, died in his sleep

Unspeakable: YouTuber

HowToBasic: YouTuber

Gaetan Dugas: Canadian flight attendant

Sameera Moussa: first Egyptian female nuclear physicist, fell off a tower while doing an experiment

Maiteryi: Indian philosopher, fate unknown

Yetnebersh Nigussie: Ethiopian disability rights activist

Enes Batur: Turkish YouTuber

IShowSpeed: American online streamer and YouTuber

Georgina Mumba: Zambian disability inclusion advocate

Hydraulic Press Channel: YouTuber who likes to crush things with a hydraulic press

Gargi Vachaknavi: Indian philosopher, fate unknown

Yaslov: crocodile who escaped from a Russian zoo, died from hypothermia

Eliza Suggs: American fish hatchery worker, killed by a lionfish

Dr. Erik J. Huffman: entrepreneur and educator

Nana Asma'u: Nigerian princess, fate unknown

Juan Carlos Ongania: Argentine coppersmith, vaporized in a hot oven

Zera Yacob: seventeenth century Ethiopian philosopher, eaten by hyenas

Vlad the Impaler: ruler of Wallachia, impaled 9,500 people to be skinned, boiled decapitated, strangled, burned, hanged, hacked, nailed, buried alive, nailed, roasted, stabbed, etc.

Ashley Hesse: VP of Policy for Indigenous Pact

Aisha Morales: morning and noon news anchor

Ruhollah Khomeini: supreme leader of Iran, died from old age

Dr. Rosa Yekuhsiyo King: founder of Tehatiw-nakhwa Language Nest

Foday Sankoh: Sierra Leone man, executed for sending bomb threat to government

Abdullah: king of Saudi Arabia, shot by a war criminal

Ashley Todd mugging hoax: student of Republican presidential candidate John McCain

Dr. Brittany Bell: dean of students at Lawrence University

Laureen Rahn: American teenager, died in an arson attack

Randy Teter: customer at a Circle K convenience store, very racist

Dr. Adriana McCleer: community partnerships supervisor for Appleton Public Library

David Kato: teacher

Alisha and Tydus Hayes: opened Pat's Rib Place

Aidin Bozorgi: Iranian mountain climber, fell off a high mountain after being hit by a mountain goat

Johnny Gosch: paperboy in West Des Moines, Iowa who vanished between 6:00 and 7:00 AM

Collin Price: president of Lac Courte Oreilles Ojibwe University
